english:
  title: A Reply to the Official Sata
  author: Lee Gyubo
  language: eng
  text: |-
    I humbly submit this letter. Upon receiving your esteemed message, I learn with great joy that you remain in good health and spirits.

    Concerning the matter you previously raised—that our sovereign did not appear but sent a great official in his stead—our small nation has explained this in our former correspondence. Though we have withdrawn to this place out of deference to your great power, our reverent regard for you remains undiminished and ever grows. We dare not transgress your stern commands, and have already dispatched a great official to await your gracious reply. Yet now you reiterate this matter, mentioning that our king did not appear and that Minister Choe came instead. These repeated reproaches weigh upon us greatly. We beseech you to consider our difficult straits and show us some measure of mercy, that we might find relief from our desperate hopes.

    As for the tokens of goodwill we have sent to the Emperor's court, though we have exhausted our efforts and spared no sincerity in their preparation, our nation's sudden migration has left us impoverished. With so few people and in such haste, we crossed the waters with meager possessions. What tributes we could offer were therefore humble and scant—mere trifles to express our loyalty. Now, receiving your message urging us to exhaust what we have and add to our previous offerings, we are overwhelmed with shame and dread.

    Regarding the dispatch of General Zhao and Song Lipzhang: our emissary Shuzhang fell grievously ill upon returning from the great nation and has not yet recovered, making immediate dispatch impossible. As for this Song Lipzhang—when our nation relocated, it was upon his counsel that we moved. Yet later, when our envoys returned from the great nation, they reported that his words did not truly reflect the great nation's intentions and could not be deemed reliable. The court therefore deliberated and concluded that this man not only stirred the people's hearts with baseless rumors but caused ten thousand to flee in panic and brought our entire nation to migrate to this distant place. His crime admits of no forgiveness. Thus he was captured and sent long ago to a remote island prison. Now, following your command, we have already sent men to fetch him and shall bring him forth. Please be assured of this. My yearning for your grace and mercy knows no bounds.
  footnotes:
    - This is a diplomatic letter from the Korean Goryeo kingdom, likely written during the Mongol invasions of the 13th century when the royal court fled to Ganghwa Island.
    - The 'great nation' (大國) refers to the Mongol Yuan Dynasty; the 'small nation' (小國) is Goryeo.
    - Song Lipzhang appears to have been an advisor whose counsel led to the kingdom's relocation, but whose trustworthiness was later questioned.
